  - m_Id: 1327761594544128
    m_Localized: "1. Concept Definition\r\n\"One Cup Two Pieces\" is the core symbol
      of Cantonese (Pearl River Delta) tea culture, meaning \"one cup of tea paired
      with two dim sum items.\" It embodies the \"morning tea\" (yum cha) ritual,
      combining tea drinking with dim sum consumption into a cultural practice integrating
      dining, socialization, and leisure.\r\n2. Core Components\r\n\u2022 \"One Cup\":
      Centered on tea\u2014traditionally robust, grease-cutting varieties like Pu'er,
      Tieguanyin, Chrysanthemum Pu'er, Shou Mei\u2014reflecting \"tea precedes food\"
      logic.\r\n\u2022 \"Two Pieces\": Two dim sum items. Early staples were sweet-savory
      Cantonese bites like char siu bao, har gow, siu mai. Later expanded to hundreds:
      ma lai go, char siu pastry, cheong fun, etc."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1328650342395904
    m_Localized: "1. Emergence: Ming-Qing Commerce\r\nAs a trading port, Guangzhou
      attracted merchants. Simple \"tea houses\" (cha ju) along Pearl River docks/markets
      (per Panyu County Annals) served traders/boatmen, forming early \"tea + dim
      sum\" culture.\r\nSource: Qu Dajun's New Accounts of Guangdong first documented
      \"Guangzhou custom: morning tea must have dim sum.\"\r\n\r\n2. Maturation:
      Teahouses & Standardization (Late Qing-Early ROC)\r\nLate 19th century: Grand
      teahouses emerged (e.g., Tao Tao Ju 1880, Lin Heung 1889). \"Weekly Dim Sum\"
      system (rotating menus) made \"One Cup Two Pieces\" a daily habit.\r\nSource:
      Guangzhou Culinary Culture (Chen Zehong, 2005): ROC-era teahouses standardized
      \"graded tea pricing + per-piece dim sum billing.\"\r\n\r\n3. Peak: Post-war
      Revival & Cultural Symbolism (1950s-Present)\r\n1956: \"Weekly Dim Sum\" innovation
      \u2192 hundreds of varieties. 2014: \"Yum cha\" became China ICH. \"One Cup
      Two Pieces\" is now a global cultural icon.\r\nSource: Encyclopedia of Cantonese
      Culture (2018): Morning tea is key for \"intergenerational bonding\" and \"business
      talks.\""
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1328925287411712
    m_Localized: "1. Social Etiquette Vehicle\r\n\u2022 Finger-tapping thanks: Legendarily
      from Qianlong incognito; became standard when receiving tea (Guangdong Folk
      Customs, 1993).\r\n\u2022 Lid-propping refill: Placing lid on pot spout signals
      server\u2014subtle communication.\r\n\r\n2. Business Civilization Microcosm\r\nMing-ROC
      teahouses were primary venues for trade talks/guild meetings (e.g., Thirteen
      Hongs merchants at Wenyuan Teahouse). Dim sum consumption intertwined with
      commerce.\r\nSource: Guangzhou History Records (2002/3): 1920s teahouses served
      100K+ daily; 70% were merchants/artisans.\r\n\r\n3. Culinary Philosophy Embodiment\r\nPairing
      logic: \"Tea cuts grease, dim sum fills stomachs\"\u2014e.g., fatty siu mai
      with Pu'er; sweet lotus buns with chrysanthemum Pu'er. Reflects TCM \"hot-cold
      balance.\""
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1329464947535872
    m_Localized: "1. Classic \"Two Pieces\"\r\n\u2022 Har Gow (shrimp dumpling):
      Early 1900s; translucent wheat starch skin. Cited in 1937 Guangzhou Bamboo
      Branch Songs: \"Guests vie for shrimp dumplings, siu mai.\"\r\n\u2022 Char
      Siu Bao: Ming Yang Xiao Lu recorded \"steamed buns with meat.\" Qing evolved
      to \"smiling\" open-top shape, symbolizing \"rising fortune.\"\r\n\r\n2. Tea
      Pairing Logic\r\n\u2022 Ripe Pu'er: With roast meats/greasy dim sum to cut
      oil (History of Guangdong Tea, 1995).\r\n\u2022 Tieguanyin: With seafood dim
      sum to enhance umami, remove fishiness.\r\n\u2022 Chrysanthemum Pu'er: Autumn/winter;
      clears heat, moistens dryness."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1329706606555136
    m_Localized: '1. ICH Protection & Innovation

      2014: "Cantonese Morning
      Tea" became China ICH. Tao Tao Ju, Guangzhou Restaurant, Lin Heung designated
      heritage bases (MCT announcement). Modern creations (e.g., "molecular har gow,"
      "bird''s nest egg tart") coexist with "Four Heavenly Kings" staples (har gow,
      siu mai, char siu bao, egg tart).



      2. Global Spread

      19th-century
      diaspora brought it to SE Asia/Europe/America. NYC/London teahouses preserve
      "One Cup Two Pieces" as cultural identity symbol.'
