  - m_Id: 1685656408453120
    m_Localized: 'Song and Yuan

      Tianfei (Mazu): Legends date to the Song dynasty.
      Lin Mo of Meizhou Island, Fujian, rescued people in distress during her lifetime.
      After her ascension, temples were built in her honor. Southern Song Liao Pengfei''s
      Record of Rebuilding Shunji Temple at Shengdun: "Surnamed Lin, from Meizhou.
      She practiced shamanism, foretelling fortunes. After death, a temple was built
      on the island... The following year (1123 CE), Lu Yundi envoys to Goryeo encountered
      storms in the East Sea. Of eight ships, seven capsized. Only his ship saw a
      goddess dancing on the mast, and it was saved. Questioning the crew, Li Zhen,
      a devotee, explained. The court granted the temple title ''Shunji'' (Favorable
      Aid)."

      Song maritime trade linked Fujian and Guangdong. Min migrants
      brought Mazu worship to Guangdong''s coast. As Liu Kezhuang noted: "Cantonese
      revere Mazu no less than Putian people."'
