  - m_Id: 1689428748693504
    m_Localized: "Records of the Plants of the South under \"Yasemin\" quotes Lu
      Jia's Travel Notes of Nanyue: \"In Nanyue, grains are bland, flowers lack fragrance\u2014only
      these two flowers (Yasemin and Molihua) are exceptionally fragrant. Transplanted
      from foreign lands, they adapt without changing, unlike oranges turning bitter
      north of the Huai River. Local women thread colored strings through their hearts
      to wear as ornaments.\""
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1689647649419264
    m_Localized: Guangzhou has always been a famous flower - Six Dynasties dynasties
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1689914994356224
    m_Localized: "Records of the Plants of the South Vol.1:\r\nYasemin and Molihua
      were transplanted from Western regions to the South Sea by foreigners. Southerners,
      enamored by their fragrance, cultivated them widely. Lu Jia's Travel Notes
      of Nanyue: \"In Nanyue, grains are bland, flowers lack fragrance\u2014only
      these two are fragrant. Transplanted from foreign lands, they adapt without
      changing, unlike oranges turning bitter...\" Women thread colored silk through
      their hearts for ornaments.\r\nMolihua resembles white roses but is more fragrant
      than Yasemin.\r\nCardamom flowers: Seedlings like reeds, leaves like ginger,
      flowers in spikes. Buds reddish, spike tips darken as leaves unfurl and blooms
      emerge. Traditionally consumed to dispel gas, dissolve phlegm, and enhance
      alcohol tolerance. In 281 CE, Jiaozhou presented a basket; the emperor verified
      its efficacy and gifted it to ministers.\r\nGalangal flowers: Stems and leaves
      resemble ginger; roots inedible. Flowers emerge between leaves as soft red
      wheat-like spikes. Decoctions treat chills effectively. Native to Jiuzhen and
      Jiaozhi.\r\nCrane grass: A vine with dust-colored, pale purple flowers. Willow-like
      short leaves. Blooms in summer, shaped like flying cranes with complete beaks,
      wings, tails, and feet. Native to South Sea. Believed to be an aphrodisiac;
      insects on it metamorphose into reddish-yellow butterflies. Women keep them
      as \"charm butterflies\" to win husbands' affection.\r\nBeautiful flowers:
      Water lily resembles lotus but has purple, thornless stems. Water banana resembles
      daylilies, purple or yellow. During Sun Xiu's reign (258-264 CE), envoys failed
      to obtain them but brought paintings."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
