  - m_Id: 1691495064170496
    m_Localized: "Qu Dajun's Guangzhou Bamboo Branch Song: \"Hibiscus too is Fusang\u2014each
      bloom aflame like sea-clouds. Worn daily by southern maidens in their hair,
      slanting on every head.\"\r\nWang Shizhen's Six Guangzhou Bamboo Branch Songs
      II: \"Plum blossoms near spring's end, hibiscus and peach urge them on. Apricots
      and loquats flood markets; jade plates hold bayberries in March.\"\r\nHuang
      Zigao's Flower Field Bamboo Branch Song: \"Regret not dwelling in Zhuangtou
      Village\u2014clothed and fed by Suxin flowers all my life.\"\r\nL\xFC Jian's
      Panyu Bamboo Branch Song: \"In March, flower sellers cross the river\u2014east
      bank fewer than west. By Suxin fields, who mourns? Only pearl girls sigh in
      vain.\"\r\nLi Huanpu's Pearl River Bamboo Branch Song: \"Today's perfect for
      Huadi strolls\u2014roses bloom amidst crape myrtles.\"\r\nZhang Qiucha's Yangcheng
      Bamboo Branch Song: \"Jasmine, roses, and cherry blossoms\u2014basket carriers
      cry their wares. Butterflies chase in pairs, following sellers into the city.\""
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 1692874809831424
    m_Localized: 'Duan Chengshi''s Miscellaneous Morsels from Youyang writes "Yasemin"
      as "Yesemi": "Yesemi comes from Fulin (Byzantium) and Persia. Stems 7-8 feet
      tall; plum-like leaves. Flowers bloom year-round, five-petaled, white, seedless.
      When blooming, fragrance fills fields, similar to Lingnan''s camphor. Westerners
      press its flowers into fragrant oil."

      The name "Suxin" emerged during
      the Five Dynasties. Compendium of Fragrant Flowers quotes Guishan Chronicles:
      "A maid of Prince Liu named Suxin was buried here; this flower grew on her
      grave." Guangzhou Chronicles cites Southern Expedition Records: "A beauty was
      buried here (west of the city) during Liu Yin''s reign; the fragrance remains
      unique." Guangzhou Chronicles: "Flower field people cultivate Suxin. As its
      spirit is a Southern Han beauty, only women may pick it."'
